                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d157">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Conger</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Pekin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-09-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 3, 1900</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>Received via Taku September 3, 1900.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>(Mr. Conger states that New York papers just received represent, through Chinese
                    minister, that Chinese Government tried continuously <pb facs="0290" n="192"
                        xml:id="pg_192"/> to protect legations from Boxers. That this is untrue;
                    that after June 20 the Boxers were organized, officered, paid, and praised by an
                    Imperial decree; that edicts may have been issued for consumption abroad, but in
                    China the Chinese Government and Boxers made common cause against everything
                    foreign. Ministers disagreeing with this policy were beheaded or kept
                    silent.)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
